Strategic Air Command, or SAC as it was chillingly known, was the blunt instrument of American strategic power for the better part of the [Cold War](/Cold_War). Active from 1946 until its dissolution in 1992, it was both a Specified Command within the [United States Department of Defense](/United_States_Department_of_Defense) and a Major Command (MAJCOM) of the [United States Air Force](/United_States_Air_Force). Its mandate was clear, and frankly, terrifying: the command and control of the nation's strategic nuclear forces. This meant the strategic bomber fleets, the [intercontinental ballistic missile](/Intercontinental_ballistic_missile) forces, and the crucial support elements like strategic [reconnaissance aircraft](/Reconnaissance_aircraft), airborne command posts, and a significant portion of the USAF's [aerial refueling](/Aerial_refueling) capacity. SAC was the embodiment of "deterrence," a word that means "we have the ability to end your existence, so you'd better behave."

The backbone of SAC was its numbered air forces: the [Second Air Force](/Second_Air_Force) (2AF), the [Eighth Air Force](/Eighth_Air_Force) (8AF), and the [Fifteenth Air Force](/Fifteenth_Air_Force) (15AF). Its headquarters, HQ SAC, was a labyrinth of directorates, managing everything from Operations & Plans and Intelligence to Command & Control, Maintenance, Training, Communications, and Personnel. Beneath that, specialized divisions like Aircraft Engineering, Missile Concept, &#91;3&#93; and Strategic Communications ensured the gears of the massive machine kept turning. At its zenith, SAC commanded an imposing force of 37 wings, organized under Air Divisions. This wasn't just a collection of planes; it was a testament to the terrifying potential of human ingenuity. We're talking 316 [B-52 Stratofortress](/Boeing_B-52_Stratofortress) bombers, capable of delivering unimaginable destruction. Add to that 56 [FB-111 Aardvarks](/General_Dynamics_F-111_Aardvark), 14 [EC-135 'Looking Glass'](/Boeing_EC-135) command and control aircraft, a fleet of 615 [KC-135 Stratotankers](/Boeing_KC-135_Stratotanker) for extended reach, several [E-4 'Nightwatch'](/Boeing_E-4) planes for airborne command, and the chilling array of 48 [LGM-25C Titan II](/LGM-25C_Titan_II) and a thousand [Minuteman](/LGM-30_Minuteman) II and III [intercontinental ballistic missiles](/Intercontinental_ballistic_missile). &#91;4&#93; &#91;5&#93; This was the arsenal that kept the other side awake at night.

The end of the [Cold War](/Cold_War) brought about a significant restructuring of the U.S. Air Force, and SAC, as it was, ceased to exist in 1992. It was disestablished as both a Specified Command and a MAJCOM. Its personnel and equipment were absorbed by other commands: the [Air Combat Command](/Air_Combat_Command) (ACC), the [Air Mobility Command](/Air_Mobility_Command) (AMC), [Pacific Air Forces](/Pacific_Air_Forces) (PACAF), [United States Air Forces in Europe](/United_States_Air_Forces_in_Europe) (USAFE), and the [Air Education and Training Command](/Air_Education_and_Training_Command) (AETC). SAC's imposing headquarters complex at [Offutt AFB](/Offutt_AFB), Nebraska, found a new purpose, becoming the home of the newly formed [United States Strategic Command](/United_States_Strategic_Command) (USSTRATCOM), a joint [Unified Combatant Command](/Unified_Combatant_Command) designed to consolidate the nation's strategic nuclear posture. The SAC name, however, wasn't entirely relegated to history. In 2009, it was reactivated and redesignated as the [Air Force Global Strike Command](/Air_Force_Global_Strike_Command) (AFGSC), inheriting the mantle of commanding all USAF bomber aircraft and the [intercontinental ballistic missile](/Intercontinental_ballistic_missile) force, effectively picking up where its predecessor left off. &#91;6&#93;

### Background

The insignia of the Strategic Air Forces of the United States during [World War II](/World_War_II) included [General](/General) [Carl Spaatz](/Carl_Spaatz)'s European command, [United States Strategic Air Forces in Europe](/United_States_Strategic_Air_Forces_in_Europe) (USSTAF), which comprised the 8AF and 15AF. In the Pacific, there was the [United States Strategic Air Forces in the Pacific](/United_States_Strategic_Air_Forces_in_the_Pacific) (USASTAT) and its [Twentieth Air Force](/Twentieth_Air_Force) (20AF). &#91;7&#93; These were the precursors, the foundational elements that would eventually coalesce into the behemoth that was SAC.

The [U.S. Army Air Forces](/U.S._Army_Air_Forces) had already engaged in extensive strategic bombing campaigns during World War II. In the [European Theater](/European_Theater), this included the [VIII Bomber Command](/VIII_Bomber_Command), which launched the first European "heavy bomber" attack by the USAAF on 17 August 1942. The [Ninth Air Force](/Ninth_Air_Force) was involved in [Operation Crossbow](/Operation_Crossbow) "No-Ball" missions as early as 5 December 1943, &#91;8&#93; while the [Twelfth Air Force](/Twelfth_Air_Force) and the [Fifteenth Air Force](/Fifteenth_Air_Force) executed bombing operations, such as the bombing of Wiener Neustadt on 2 November 1943 during [Operation Pointblank](/Operation_Pointblank). The air plan for [Operation Overlord](/Operation_Overlord), the strategic bombing of Germany and its forces in preparation for the [1944 invasion of France](/Operation_Overlord), saw the coordination of multiple Air Forces, primarily from the [USAAF](/USAAF) and the [Royal Air Force](/Royal_Air_Force) ([RAF](/RAF)). Command of these operations eventually transitioned to the [Supreme Commander of the Allied Expeditionary Force](/Supreme_Commander_of_the_Allied_Expeditionary_Force) on 14 April 1944.

Even as the war drew to a close, planning for a postwar, independent U.S. Air Force was underway. By the fall of 1945, the [Simpson Board](/William_Hood_Simpson) was tasked with charting this new course, "...the reorganization of the Army and the Air Force...". &#91;9&#93; This foresight led to a consensus in January 1946 between Generals [Eisenhower](/Dwight_D._Eisenhower) and [Spaatz](/Carl_Andrew_Spaatz) regarding the Air Force's future structure. It was envisioned as comprising the Strategic Air Command, the [Air Defense Command](/Air_Defense_Command), the [Tactical Air Command](/Tactical_Air_Command), the [Air Transport Command](/Air_Transport_Command_(United_States_Air_Force)), and the supporting commands like the [Air Technical Service Command](/Air_Technical_Service_Command), [Air Training Command](/Air_Education_and_Training_Command), the [Air University](/Air_University_(United_States_Air_Force)), and the [Air Force Applied Tactics School](/Army_Air_Forces_School_of_Applied_Tactics). &#91;9&#93; It was a grand vision, laying the groundwork for a force that would shape global politics for decades.

### Establishment and Transfer to USAF

[Boeing B-47B Stratojet](/Boeing_B-47_Stratojet) executing a [rocket-assisted take off](/Rocket-assisted_take_off) (RATO) on 15 April 1954. A testament to the technological leaps of the era.

• For a list of the 32 "airfields and installations" for which SAC assumed jurisdiction &#91;10&#93; on 21 March 1946, see [Strategic Air Command bases](/List_of_Strategic_Air_Command_bases).

Strategic Air Command's origins trace back to the [U.S. Army Air Forces](/U.S._Army_Air_Forces) on 21 March 1946. It was established upon the redesignation of [Continental Air Forces](/Continental_Air_Forces) (CAF), the wartime command responsible for the air defense of the continental United States (CONUS). At that time, the CAF headquarters was situated at [Bolling Field](/Bolling_Field) (later [Bolling AFB](/Bolling_AFB)) in the District of Columbia. SAC inherited these facilities, but it wasn't long before the command moved its headquarters (HQ SAC) to nearby [Andrews Field](/Andrews_Field) (later [Andrews AFB](/Andrews_AFB)), Maryland. It operated as a tenant there until it assumed full control of Andrews Field in October 1946. &#91;11&#93;

SAC initially comprised 37,000 USAAF personnel, a substantial force for the time. &#91;12&#93; Beyond Bolling Field and Andrews Field, SAC also took charge of:

• [Roswell AAF](/Walker_Air_Force_Base), New Mexico (later renamed Roswell AFB, then [Walker AFB](/Walker_AFB)), which housed the USAAF's sole nuclear-capable bomb wing. This was a critical asset, signaling the dawn of the nuclear age for air power.

• [Smoky Hill AAF](/Schilling_Air_Force_Base), Kansas (later renamed Smoky Hill AFB, then [Schilling AFB](/Schilling_AFB)).

In addition to these, seven other CAF bases were transferred to SAC on 21 March 1946, and they remained under SAC's operational umbrella even after the establishment of the U.S. Air Force as an independent service in 1947. These installations included:

• [Castle Field](/Castle_Air_Force_Base), California (later [Castle Air Force Base](/Castle_Air_Force_Base))

• [Clovis AAF](/Cannon_Air_Force_Base), New Mexico (later [Cannon Air Force Base](/Cannon_Air_Force_Base))

• [Fort Worth AAF](/Carswell_Air_Force_Base), Texas (later [Carswell Air Force Base](/Carswell_Air_Force_Base))

• [Davis-Monthan Field](/Davis-Monthan_Air_Force_Base), Arizona (later [Davis-Monthan Air Force Base](/Davis-Monthan_Air_Force_Base))

• [Rapid City AAF](/Ellsworth_Air_Force_Base), South Dakota (later [Ellsworth Air Force Base](/Ellsworth_Air_Force_Base))

• [MacDill Field](/MacDill_Air_Force_Base), Florida (later [MacDill Air Force Base](/MacDill_Air_Force_Base))

• [Mountain Home AAF](/Mountain_Home_Air_Force_Base), Idaho (later [Mountain Home Air Force Base](/Mountain_Home_Air_Force_Base))

On 31 March 1946, another significant installation was brought under SAC's command:

• [Kirtland Field](/Kirtland_Air_Force_Base), New Mexico (later [Kirtland Air Force Base](/Kirtland_Air_Force_Base))

Under the command of General [George C. Kenney](/George_C._Kenney), the first Commander in Chief of SAC, the initial units reporting to headquarters on 21 March 1946 included the [Second Air Force](/Second_Air_Force), the [IX Troop Carrier Command](/IX_Troop_Carrier_Command), and the [73d Air Division](/73d_Air_Division).

The [Fifteenth Air Force](/Fifteenth_Air_Force) was assigned to SAC on 31 March, with its [263rd Army Air Force Base Unit](/263rd_Army_Air_Force_Base_Unit)—along with SAC's radar detachments &#91;13&#93;—transferring directly under HQ SAC on the same date. The IX Troop Carrier Command, however, was inactivated on that day, its assets absorbed by SAC. Even with the ongoing postwar demobilization, which saw eight of the ten assigned bomb groups inactivated before the [Eighth Air Force](/Eighth_Air_Force) joined SAC on 7 June 1946, SAC pressed on. The command focused on the training and evaluation of bomber crews and units that remained active. [Radar Bomb Scoring](/Radar_Bomb_Scoring) became the preferred method for assessing bomber crew performance. In 1946, 888 simulated bomb runs were scored, a number that would escalate to 2,449 by 1947. &#91;15&#93; &#91;13&#93; In the shadow of the atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki, SAC became the focal point of the nation's nuclear strike capability. This strategic importance was underscored by Joint Chiefs of Staff (JCS) Publication 1259/27 on 12 December 1946, which stipulated that "...the 'air atomic' strategic air force should only come under the orders of the JCS." &#91;7&#93;

Beyond its primary bombing mission, SAC also dedicated significant resources to aerial reconnaissance. In 1946, its reconnaissance fleet consisted of F-2 photo variants of the [C-45 Expeditor](/C-45_Expeditor). By 1947, however, SAC had acquired an F-9C squadron, comprising twelve photo-reconnaissance variants of the [B-17G Flying Fortress](/B-17G_Flying_Fortress). An F-13 squadron, later re-designated as the [RB-29 Superfortress](/B-29_Superfortress), was also established. SAC conducted routine reconnaissance missions near Soviet borders or within the 12-mile international waters limit, though some missions did venture into Soviet airspace. These flights, conducted at altitudes above 30,000 feet and speeds exceeding 300 knots, made interception by Soviet forces difficult until the introduction of the [MiG-15](/MiG-15) jet fighter in 1948. &#91;16&#93; [Project Nanook](/Project_Nanook), the first classified reconnaissance effort of the Cold War, utilized early RB-29 missions for mapping and visual reconnaissance in the Arctic and along the northern Soviet coast. Subsequent projects included LEOPARD along the [Chukchi Peninsula](/Chukchi_Peninsula), followed by RICKRACK, STONEWORK, and COVERALLS. &#91;17&#93;

In 1946, the United States possessed a mere nine atomic bombs, with only twenty-seven [B-29s](/B-29) capable of delivering them at any given time. &#91;18&#93; Furthermore, it was later revealed that a nuclear strike by the [509th Composite Bomb Group](/509th_Bomb_Wing) between 1947 and 1948 would have required five to six days just to transfer custody of the bombs from [United States Atomic Energy Commission](/United_States_Atomic_Energy_Commission) (AEC) sites, deploy the aircraft, and prepare for launch. &#91;19&#93; &#91;20&#93; The relentless budget and personnel cuts following the war had a corrosive effect on SAC. Major General Clements McMullen, the Deputy Commander, implemented mandated force reductions, leading to a significant decline in SAC's operational readiness. By the end of 1947, only two of SAC's eleven groups were considered combat-ready. &#91;7&#93; After the 1948 [Bikini Atoll](/Bikini_Atoll) nuclear tests, the "Half Moon" Joint Emergency War Plan, developed in May 1948, &#91;21&#93; proposed dropping 50 atomic bombs on twenty Soviet cities. &#91;18&#93; &#58;&#8202;68&#8202; President [Harry S. Truman](/Harry_S._Truman) approved this plan during the [Berlin Blockade](/Berlin_Blockade) in June 1948, &#91;18&#93; &#58;&#8202;68–9&#8202; and B-29s were subsequently sent to Europe in July. &#91;22&#93; SAC also deployed special ELINT RB-29s to detect improved Soviet [radars](/Radar) and, in collaboration with the 51st Air Force Base Unit, monitored radioactive fallout from Soviet atomic testing on [Novaya Zemlya](/Novaya_Zemlya).

In terms of infrastructure and resource allocation, SAC continued to absorb an ever-increasing share of USAF resources and budget. In 1947, prior to the USAF's establishment as a distinct service, construction began on [Limestone AAF](/Loring_AFB), Maine (later renamed [Loring AFB](/Loring_AFB)), a new SAC installation specifically designed to accommodate the colossal [B-36 Peacemaker](/B-36_Peacemaker). Between 30 April and 1 September 1947, [Fort Dix AAF](/McGuire_Air_Force_Base), New Jersey (later [McGuire AFB](/McGuire_AFB)); [Spokane AAF](/Fairchild_Air_Force_Base), Washington (later [Fairchild AFB](/Fairchild_AFB)); and [Wendover Field](/Wendover_Air_Force_Base), Utah (later [Wendover AFB](/Wendover_AFB)) were also transferred to SAC. Following the USAF's establishment as an independent service, SAC's bases within the United States &#91;23&#93; included:

• [Castle Air Force Base](/Castle_Air_Force_Base), California

