### Overseas Components

[Strategic Air Command in the United Kingdom](/Strategic_Air_Command_in_the_United_Kingdom) represented one of the command's largest overseas concentrations of forces. Additionally, forces under SAC's [16th Air Force](/16th_Air_Force) were stationed at air bases in North Africa, Spain, and Turkey throughout the 1950s and 1960s.

[SAC "Provisional" wings](/List_of_USAF_Provisional_Wings_assigned_to_Strategic_Air_Command) were also located at [Kadena AB](/Kadena_AB), Okinawa, and [U-Tapao Royal Thai Navy Airfield](/U-Tapao_Royal_Thai_Navy_Airfield) / [U-Tapao AB](/U-Tapao_Royal_Thai_Navy_Airfield), Thailand, during the [Vietnam War](/Vietnam_War).

SAC also maintained bomber, tanker, and/or reconnaissance aircraft assets at the former [Ramey AFB](/Ramey_AFB) in Puerto Rico during the 1950s, 1960s, and 1970s. Furthermore, it operated from bases such as [Andersen AFB](/Andersen_AFB), Guam; [RAF Mildenhall](/RAF_Mildenhall), [RAF Fairford](/RAF_Fairford), and [RAF Alconbury](/RAF_Alconbury) in the United Kingdom; [Moron AB](/Moron_AB) in Spain; [Lajes Field](/Lajes_Field) in the Azores (Portugal); [Diego Garcia](/Diego_Garcia), BIOT; and the former [NAS Keflavik](/NAS_Keflavik), Iceland, through the 1990s.

SAC also conducted operations from [RAF Fairford](/RAF_Fairford), [RAF Alconbury](/RAF_Alconbury), and [RAF Mildenhall](/RAF_Mildenhall) in the United Kingdom; [Moron AB](/Moron_AB) in Spain; [Lajes Field](/Lajes_Field) in the Azores (Portugal); [RAF Akrotiri](/RAF_Akrotiri) in Cyprus; [Incirlik AB](/Incirlik_AB) in Turkey; [Diego Garcia](/Diego_Garcia) in the [British Indian Ocean Territory](/British_Indian_Ocean_Territory); and from multiple air bases in Egypt, Saudi Arabia, Oman, and the United Arab Emirates during the first [Gulf War](/Gulf_War) (Operations [Desert Shield](/Desert_Shield) and [Desert Storm](/Desert_Storm)) from 1990 to 1991. &#91;101&#93;

***

There. That's the bare bones of it. A history of immense power, chilling responsibility, and ultimately, an era that defined global politics. It’s a story of technology, strategy, and the constant, gnawing fear of annihilation. Don't expect me to wax poetic about it. It just *was*.